bay_data <- read_csv("baytractdata2018.csv")
jefferson_data <- read_csv("jeffersontractdata2018.csv")
combined_data <- read_csv("jeffersonbay2018.csv")

Topic and Variables

My data analysis uses tract-level data to explore poverty, public assistance, and high-school graduation rates in two regions of California: the Bay Area and an informal region called Jefferson comprised of rural counties in Northeast California. Jefferson is a primarily rural region, while the Bay Area is primarily urban.

I have quite a large set of variables, most of which are continuous. Part of this is because Ive chosen to look at all three poverty variables as defined by the 5-Year ACS as well as differences in public assistance including and excluding Social Security Income.

List of Variables

  1. Total Population: total_popE = (continuous)
  2. Total below 150 % poverty level: low_income (continuous)
  3. Percent of population receiving public assistance (including SSI): (continuous)
  4. Percent of population receiving cash public assistance (including food stamps/SNAP): (continuous)
  5. High School Graduates: (categorical, >83% meets statewide average)
  6. Some college or Associates: (categorical, >29% meets statewide average)
  7. Bachelors or higher: (categorical, >33% meets statewide average)
  8. County (categorical)
  9. Region (categorical)

Organization and Credit

Because Ive chosen a large number of continuous variables and per the assignment instructions to test every possible relationship, there are quite a few calculations in this analysis. To make the document readable and emphasize salient information, my code chunks are all collapsible. If the reader would like to view all the code, you can use the code button at the top right corner of the screen to turn all code on or off. Additionally, you can view individual code chunks as desired by clicking the code button above the output for which youd like to see the code.

Tabs are organized by the type of test being performed. Within each tab, calculations are organized by whether or not they are being performed on the Bay Area Region data, Jefferson Region data, or both regions combined.

The relationships between all variables as shown by the tests are all described in the Relationship Strengths and Statistical Significance tab. The calculations Ive chosen to visualize and analyze are in the Discussion, Visualizations, and Comparisons tab.

I used Cats example and Caroles tutorial as the basis for organization and exploration. Dylan shared a code function with me that allowed me to visualize my correlations in one table, which was extremely useful for visualizing correlations in one space. Mel shared the code for creating a floating table of contents in our Tuesday class meeting, which ended up being so essential for organizing this analysis in a way that was manageable. And Ryan reminded me that this was assignment 3 and not 2 Thanks all!

Chi-square test

Bay and Jefferson Combined Chi-square Calculations:

Because region and county are the categorical variables Im comparing with my high school graduation variable, Ive chosen to perform the tests with the combined data.

chi1_combined <- chisq.test(combined_data$region, combined_data$majority_grads)
chi1_combined
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  combined_data$region and combined_data$majority_grads
## X-squared = 4.5629, df = 1, p-value = 0.03267
chi1_combined$observed
##                     combined_data$majority_grads
## combined_data$region FALSE TRUE
##            Bay         191 1388
##            Jefferson     4   90
chi1_combined$expected
##                     combined_data$majority_grads
## combined_data$region     FALSE       TRUE
##            Bay       184.04363 1394.95637
##            Jefferson  10.95637   83.04363

Relationship Strengths and Statistical Significance

This section contains a summary of the strengths and/or significance of each relationship tested per region. I chose to compile my descriptions here so they can be viewed with easy comparison by region. Theyre organized by test type and the order they appear within teach test tab, so the reader can reference back to the other tabs if they would like to view the code or calculation output in further detail.

Bay Area Correlation Descriptions

Significant relationships are listed below for each region, and defined by the following thresholds:

.00-.19 = very weak .20-.39 = weak .40-.59 = moderate .60-.79 = strong .80-1.0 = very strong

  1. There is a significant, weak, negative correlation (-.2571) between total population and public assistance in the Bay Area tracts in the dataset.
  2. There is a significant, very strong, positive correlation (.7964) between low income and cash assistance in the Bay Area tracts in the dataset.

Jefferson Correlation Descriptions

  1. There is a significant, moderate, negative correlation (-.4898) between total population and public assistance in the Jefferson Region tracts in the dataset. 2.There is a significant, weak, positive correlation (.2737) between low income and public assistance in the Jefferson Region tracts in the dataset. 3.There is a significant, strong, positive correlation (.6569) between low income and cash assistance in the Jefferson Region tracts in the dataset. 4.There is a significant, weak, positive correlation (.2457) between total population and public assistance in the Jefferson Region tracts in the dataset.

Bay and Jefferson T-Test Descriptions

In the Bay Area t-tests, there are significant relationships between the following: 1. low income and high school graduation rate 2. public assistance and high school graduation rate 3. cash assistance and high school graduation rate 4. low income and bachelors degree rates 5. public assistance and bachelors degree rates 6. cash assistance and bachelors degree rates

In the Jefferson t-tests, there are significant relationships between the following: 1. public assistance and some college or associates degree rates 2. cash assistance and bachelors degree rates

Bay and Jefferson Chi-Square Test Descriptions

My tests showed that there are statistically significant relationships between county and education rates and region and education rates with the caveat that there are multiple counties where the observed and expected values are less than 5, which compromises the validity of results.

Bay and Jefferson ANOVA Test Descriptions

My ANOVA tests between county and continuous variables found significant relationships between county and all other variables in both regions (though p-values for the Bay Area were universally smaller than in the Jefferson Region. )

Visualizations

Bay and Jefferson Low Income

There is a weaker correlation between population and poverty levels in the Bay Area, where there are more people per county, and a greater diversity of areas and tracts, and their respective incomes.

ggplot(bay_data, aes(x = total_popE, y = low_income)) + 
    geom_point(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.25) +

Region and Poverty

One of the most surprising findings this analysis is that Jefferson region has a higher mean number of people per tract living below the poverty line. While more people overall in the Bay Region live below poverty, proportionally more people in the Jefferson region live in poverty.

ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = region, y = low_income)) +
  geom_violin() +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Region",
